ADOLESCENT BLACK MALES’ DRUG TRAFFICKING AND ADDICTION
Three Theoretical Perspectives
SHARON E. MOORE Seton Hill College
The purpose of this article is to help explain the incidence of drug trafficking and chemical dependency among adolescent Black males. The use of drugs by Black adolescents is of particular interest because of the damaging effects that drug use has on both the individual and his or her community. After briefly discussing the nature and scope of the drug problem within this population and the incidence of chemical abuse among Black youths, the author discusses the social science theories of Emile Durkheim, Karl Marx, and Molefi Asante in an effort to bring about a better understanding of the behaviors, and the consequences of those behaviors, of young Black males who participate in the distribution of illegal drugs and/or become dependent on illicit chemicals.
SCOPE AND NATURE OF THE PROBLEM: THE BLACK MALE EXPERIENCE
The latest figures from the National Institute on Drug Abuse (1988) indicate that 18.7% of all Black youths between the ages of 12 and 17 have a history of drug experimentation. There are no available figures for this age group by sex. Black males are of particular interest because statistically Black males appear to be more at risk for drug abuse than are Black females. According to the National Institute on Drug Abuse (1988), 43.6% of all Blacks
