From an economic perspective, drug dealing is very profitable. A teenager can make from $300 to $1,200 and more per day selling drugs. With the present state of the economy, all too often the minimum wage jobs that are available to this age group cannot compete with the financial rewards of drug selling.
Drug use among Black adolescents is particularly damaging from both a social and health perspective. Drug addiction eventually leads these adolescents into activities that in turn lead to further involvement with drugs and criminal activity (Gibbs, 1984). The criminal activity may range from drug dealing to prostitution in order to support a habit. These activities also place the user at an increased risk of contracting the AIDS virus from IV drug use and of being arrested and incarcerated; both risks tend to further alienate the adolescent from the mainstream (Gibbs, 1984). As the addiction
progresses, the individual tends to lose interest in work and school,
and getting high becomes an obsession. Eventually the individual is psychologically divorced from family and significant others and becomes useless to both himself and the community of which he is a part. The adolescent is also placed at risk of early death from an overdose or as a result of the lifestyle and subculture inherent in addiction. Chemical use is involved in approximately 50% of all violent deaths; much higher rates (i.e., 70% to 80%) have been reported for specific forms of violent death such as homicide (Gibbs, 1984).
