THEORETICAL ASSUMPTIONS THAT MAY HELP TO EXPLAIN THE NATURE AND SCOPE OF THE PROBLEM
Three theoretical assumptions are used in this article in an attempt to develop a better understanding of the nature and scope of the problem of Black male teenage drug abuse. These perspectives are derived from the theory of suicide as proposed by Emile Durkheim (1951), the Karl Marx (Thcker, 1978) theory of capitalism, and Molefi Kete Asante’s Afrocentric theory of social change (1980).
THE DURKHEIMIAN PERSPECTIVE
Because one never truly knows the composition of the drug being taken, the drug abuser knowingly places himself at great risk for physical harm or even death when abusing drugs. Overdose from heroin or crack/cocaine may be a result of the addict receiving a drug that is &dquo;taken combined with concurrent use of alcohol and other sedatives,&dquo; and the addict may encounter further problems due to the &dquo;difficulty posed by adulterants used to cut heroin&dquo; (Inciardi, 1986).
Professionals involved in counseling heroin and cocaine addicts found that some of these individuals acknowledged that the use of these drugs was risk taking and had the potential to be a fatal event because one never truly knows the composition of the substance being used. When death from a drug overdose occurred in the community, some addicts reported that they would then seek out the supplier of the drug that caused the death with the rationale that if the drug was powerful enough to cause death, it must have been of such quality to produce a &dquo;good high.&dquo; Even in light of this
information, many individuals still continue to choose chemical
dependency over abstinence. The author postulates that heroin and
cocaine addiction are slow forms of suicide because the addict
knows that his chances of death are much greater as a result of
physical complications of his disease, overdose, or the concomitants of the lifestyle inherent within the subculture of drug abusers.
