Durkheim defines suicide as &dquo;any death which is the direct or indirect result of a positive or negative act accomplished by the victim himself’ (Durkheim, 1951). Durkheim suggested that there is a collective force compelling men to kill themselves that &dquo;only gradually penetrates them&dquo; (Durkheim, 1951). The propensity for
self murder is not within the individual but lies without and is the result of certain social forces.
Durkheim specifies four types of suicide: egoistic, altruistic,
anomic, and fatalistic. Of these four types, anomic and fatalistic can
best be used to explain the drug user’s behavior. Anomic suicide results &dquo;from a great change in a person’s family relationships, career, health or other important aspects of life&dquo; (Durkheim, 1951). Suicide is a function of the regulatory mechanism of society on the individual. When a person has been accustomed to having needs and satisfactions regulated by society, the individual’s inner system is thrown into a state of disequilibrium as a result of upset in his life balance, and he then becomes susceptible to anomic suicide. This may help to explain the drug abuser’s choice to continue the addiction. For instance, while attending school he may have worked part-time at a department store located in his neighborhood. He became accustomed to a certain lifestyle and having certain needs met by his society. Through employment, he had the means to participate in social functions and events such as movies and concerts. He could also buy various types of clothing and personal items when desired or needed. When the department store closes
down and relocates to a suburban section of his town, the individual, now unemployed, is thrown into chaos. If this state of unemploy-
ment becomes a chronic condition and if there are other stress
variables in the young man’s life, such as poverty or social and peer pressure toward materialism, the ultimate outcome of the individual
may be suicide. Faced with diminishing resources and the need to draw upon his own strengths, he is now in a position of susceptibility to suicide or is susceptible to a lifestyle (i.e., pushing drugs)
that leads to the use of heroin or cocaine.
Fatalism, as defined by Durkheim, &dquo;is a condition of excessive regulations of persons with futures pitilessly blocked and passions violently choked by oppressive discipline&dquo; (Peck, 1979, p.114). The
