The addict’s sense of self-worth is greatly diminished as he becomes engrossed in his addiction and loses interest in other areas of his life. He develops a need to belong only to his peer group of other addicts. It is important to him to gain membership into this group and to be accepted by the group members. However, because of the lifestyle and self-centered orientation of addicts (i.e., every man for himself in obtaining the drug and paraphernalia), the individual addict never really feels that he belongs to something
greater than himself. Thus even among his peers he is isolated.
&dquo;Feelings of guilt and shame about chemical dependency are normal. Shame is a feeling of self-loathing, self-negating, selfdisgust, and guilt is a feeling of responsibility for having done or not done something&dquo; (&dquo;Shame in Alcoholism,&dquo; 1988, p. 2). These personality deficits indicate that there is a lack of sufficient self-resources for the person to function adequately in society. According to Durkheim, the stronger the forces throwing the individual into his own resources, the greater the suicide rate in the society in which
this occurs.
