Durkheim refers to the social currents of particular time periods as exerting a certain amount of force on the individual toward self-murder. One of these currents is pessimism. Life for the addict as described by Milby ( 1981 ) is repressive and mundane. The daily activity of obtaining the drug is a routine devoid of meaning beyond the temporary satisfaction of self. This activity, coupled with the despair of being unemployed, the sense of hopelessness brought on by poverty, and living in a society that both fears and discriminates against the Black man, often perpetuates willful self-destructive behavior that may eventually lead to death.
THE MARXIAN PERSPECTIVE
Karl Marx’s theory of capitalism is used as the second theoretical assumption to help explain, from an economic perspective, why many young Black males become involved with drug trafficking and eventual chemical dependency. There are multiple forms of drug use; for the sake of simplicity the author will refer to heroin when relating to Marx’s theory although the economics of cocaine
distribution are similar to those of heroin.
Heroin is derived from the opium plant, cultivated and refined and then shipped to the United States and other areas of the world via airways and waterways for distribution. Before the drug is shipped for distribution, it is approximately 99% pure. Heroin is usually imported in quantities of kilograms. Once it reaches the
United States, it is &dquo;cut&dquo; or diluted as many as 6 to 12 times, which
results in a street heroin that is only 1% to 10% pure (Krivanek, 1988; McDonald, 1989).
Capitalism is a social and economic system whose primary objective is the acquisition of wealth and the accumulation of capital. According to Marx, the capitalists are the ruling class of society. In this system, labor is bought for a contracted period of time with wages. Marx states that what is really being bought in
this transaction is labor power. Labor power is the force and energy
that goes into the production process. Because of the competitive nature of capitalism for the accumulation of profit, a continuous rivalry exists among the capitalists. The capitalist is economically
