107
successful to the extent that he can use technology and manipulate the exploitation of the proletariat. The competitive nature of capitalism forces each entrepreneur to continuously struggle to undermine the price of his competitor. Those who own and operate larger businesses prevail over the small-business owners. In this system, the larger entrepreneurs have access to greater resources and can produce on a more cost-efficient basis. This, in turn, causes the
demise of the small-business owner and enables the former to
absorb the capital of the latter. Capitalism is built on the control over work and the economy and &dquo;the daily oppression of labor&dquo; (Tucker, 1978, p. 204).
&dquo;Within the capitalistic system of drug trafficking there are several levels of the distribution system from the importer to the addict and two economic activities may be taking place at each level: dilution of the heroin to a lower level of potency and repackaging it into smaller quantities for transaction at the next level&dquo; (Brown & Silverman, 1973, p. 52; Krivanek, 1988). The individuals involved in the trafficking system are the importer, the kilo connection, the weight dealers, and the jugglers. The importer splits the kilogram for sale to the kilo connection. The kilo connection then dilutes the drug by half strength and repackages it for sale to the weight dealer. &dquo;The last three levels in the distribution system represent levels at which both consumption and sale take place&dquo; (Brown & Silverman, 1973, p. 53). The weight dealers dilute the heroin by half for sale to the street dealers for dilution and resale to the jugglers. The jugglers usually consume one fourth to one third of the heroin they buy from the weight dealer and sell the remainder of the drug to the addict.
From a Marxian perspective, the capitalists in this system are
those individuals who are involved with sale and distribution of the
drug up to but not including those who actually consume the
substance. Those individuals who are involved in the distribution
of illegal drugs but who do not themselves consume the drug are the beneficiaries of the system in that they gain the most economic profit. Heroin trafficking is phenomenal in terms of its revenueproducing potential. For instance, a kilogram of morphine base can be sold in Italy for $12,000-$13,000. It can then be converted to
