Two classes of individuals are said to emerge from within
capitalistic society. They are the proletariat and the bourgeoisie. The bourgeoisie are the ruling class of society who own the means of social production. In the context of addiction, the dealers are the capitalists and power elite who usurp power and authority over the working class (the addict and the juggler). The proletariat are the working class or laborers of society. They have been forced by the capitalist into an economic and social position of deprivation. As with the addicted individual, their relationship to the bourgeoisie is cyclical in nature. They are dependent upon the bourgeoisie for the end products of their labor (commodities) and will sell themselves to the capitalists for lower than wanted wages in order to buy the necessary means of subsistence, in this case drugs. These means of subsistence are immediately consumed and thus the cycle continues. &dquo;The means of subsistence is that which is absolutely requisite to keep the laborer in bare existence as a laborer&dquo; (Tucker, 1978, p. 209). The juggler, who is the lowest level capitalist within the drug-dealing market, immediately consumes the drug to support his habit and in effect is transformed from being a capitalist to being a proletarian through this process. Jugglers work long hours at grievous labor to secure the bare necessities for minimal existence. The juggler is exploited at every opportunity by the bourgeoisie. The capitalist spends as little as possible on the necessities of the laborer but will exact maximum benefit from him while he is being employed. The capitalist is benefited by the juggler’s willingness
to work at all hours in unfavorable and hazardous environments.
The addict and the drug juggler are synonymous with the proletariat from a Marxist scheme. Because of their psychological and physical dependency upon the drug, both are in a subordinate position and will subject themselves and allow themselves to be subjected to subhuman conditions, such as prostitution, in order to obtain the drug (means of subsistence). The social relationship that exists between the proletariat and the bourgeoisie is reciprocal; neither can exist without the products of the other. Heroin for the proletariat becomes a type of &dquo;opium of the masses&dquo; (Ticker, 1978,
