A reserve army of unemployed persons is maintained and is functional within the capitalist system. This reserve army continuously keeps a restraint upon wages. Therefore, for example, the drug lord will never have to pay the street dealer anything above the negligible amount for his labor because others are readily available to take his place. What constitutes a negligible amount of money for the drug lord may actually seem monumental to the young Black male, especially if he comes from a background of economic deprivation. One young Black drug dealer, who resides in Washington, D.C., made earnings of $20,000 per week selling cocaine for the Columbians (Kasarda & Williams, 1989), and another youth working within a cocaine distribution ring located in Omaha, Nebraska netted $1,200 per day (Mayer, 1989). The young Black male may therefore be enticed to sell drugs because of the large sums of money that can be made by doing so, but in actuality he will never obtain the financial gain from drug trafficking that the drug lord realizes. As a result of being alienated from the legal capitalist system (i.e., the employment sector), the young Black male may turn to the illegal sector (i.e., drug distribution) as a economic means to survival (Gibbs, 1988; Stickland, 1989).
The reserve army of street dealers will be available to the drug lord because he has made the street dealers either psychologically dependent for the acquisition of material wealth and/or physically dependent upon chemicals. From a Marxian perspective, it would appear that drug distribution, which in many instances leads to the addiction of the distributor, could be an influence on the youth’s decision to use drugs, especially in light of this group’s present
economic situation.
