111
past and future. When a people are limited in their knowledge about themselves, their self-confidence is weakened, and subsequently they may not always operate in their own best interest. They may participate in self-destructive behavior, such as abusing drugs, because of a lack of self-confidence and self-esteem, which results from being devalued and being limited in their understanding of their greatness as a people. However, when a people have a good sense of their past and future, which emphasizes their greatness, they are enabled to have a true sense of their destiny and potential, which acts as a catalyst to help the individual(s) within the group develop self-respect and build character.
Asante asserts that people of African descent, regardless of their present geographical location and social position, have historically been denied a true and accurate account of their history and contributions to society because of a European model of social science, which, according to Akbar (1984), has been traditionally used as the model of normality. The European model of social science places Europeans and their culture as the world’s point of reference. All behaviors and values of non-European people are seen as either deviant or normal to the degree that these are similar or dissimilar to European culture and values.
Asante asserts that African people have been &dquo;whitewashed&dquo; into thinking that the European perspective is the only world perspective and thus need to be psychologically liberated from this viewpoint. Afro-Americans and African people need to break away from Eurocentrism and begin to look at the world from a different perspective and reality, namely their own. Only to the extent that African people reeducate themselves about themselves does Asante feel that they will be able to begin the process of total liberation from oppression and domination.
Afrocentricity is a pro-African theory that makes African values and experiences the norm by which people of African descent should be viewed. The Afrocentric perspective encourages community among African people instead of the individualistic orientation that Akbar (1984) states is a part of the European perspective of life. Whatever is best for the people as a group is ascribed to rather than only those things that will benefit the individual. Afrocentricity
