encourages race pride among African people and lifts to a higher level their consciousness of themselves and about what their position in the world should be. Their position should not be subservient or in any way less than equal to Whites.
According to Asante, Afrocentricity is the outgrowth of a collective consciousness among people with African roots, whose goal is to operate for the best interest of African people. The collective consciousness that Asante describes is the ability and &dquo;power of a group of people to think in the same direction&dquo; (Asante, 1980, p. 79). It is a positiveness of mind that stresses victory over any form of oppression. This consciousness among African people has developed and is only perpetuated as they understand the relatedness of their history to their present and future reality. Thus the Afrocentric collective consciousness is brought about through reading and study about Africa and African culture and civilization and through travel to the African continent. This consciousness shuns all things that work against Black people.
Afrocentric philosophy denounces drug abuse among African people, and Asante indicates that the use of &dquo;unnatural substances&dquo; is unhealthy. The use of drugs clouds the mind of the individual.
Individuals need to have their minds cleansed and free from chemi-
cals in order to be able to think clearly regarding their own best interests and to be able to make positive life decisions.
Unless African people are able to relinquish thinking only from a European point of view, Asante indicates that they are mentally enslaved. As people and individuals’ consciousness or way of thinking is raised, they begin to be transformed in their attitudes and behaviors and take on new behaviors, perspectives, and approaches to living and begin to view the world and their reality differently (Asante, 1980).
DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSION
Three theoretical perspectives were discussed that helped the author to explain the incidence of chemical dependency among
