Black adolescents. The theories were those of suicide as proposed by Emile Durkheim, capitalism as explained by Karl Marx, and Molefi Asante’s theory of Afrocentricity.
Durkheim’s theory of suicide helped to explain that because of
the numerous adverse socioeconomic factors that operate in the life
of the young Black male, many give in to the negative sociogenic force of the illicit drug culture as either a psychological or physiological escape from their reality. The young Black male who may himself become chemically dependent while trafficking drugs will always be in a lower class economic position because he will never rise above being dependent upon the drug supplier for the support of his habit. As a result, he may develop deeper feelings of selfinadequacy and low self-worth. Hence a vicious cycle of selfdefeating behavior may develop, and again he may become suscep-
tible to suicidal behavior.
Karl Marx’s theory of capitalism shed light on the use of or trafficking of illicit drugs by young Black males as a means of economic survival. Through the media, the American advertising industry sends young Black males a gamut of messages regarding those material elements that make up what is considered by American society to be &dquo;the good life.&dquo; The young Black male may be influenced by these messages to have similar aspirations for some of these material possessions. From the viewpoint of drug trafficking as an economic adventure, the young Black male may be led to believe that he will be able to provide for the basic necessities and some of the luxuries of life through the profits gained via the distribution of drugs.
According to Asante, an individual participates in self-destructive and defeating behavior and thought processes in part as a result of a lack of knowledge of his people’s history and achievements. Once free from his behavior, these youths can hopefully go on to be productive individuals for themselves, their community, and the larger society.
The theories of Durkheim, Marx, and Asante appear to be
compatible in that all three concepts are oriented toward the youth’s present circumstances and operate from the perspective of the need
