for positive changes within the youth’s environment in an effort to thwart self-destructive behavior (i.e., the use of illicit drugs). The author feels that the Black male’s environment (i.e., socioeconomic situation) can play a major role in his choice to use or sell drugs.
The three theories have implications for possible solutions for decreasing the drug problem in the area of chemical dependency treatment. Chemical dependency treatment programs are vehicles through which these youths can free themselves from addiction and subsequently from the negative and damaging effects of addiction on their lives. From a Durkheimian perspective, effective drug treatment could reduce the incidence of drug abuse among young Black males by building self-esteem, courage, and a sense of belonging to a collectivity larger than self that would enable them to face many of life’s obstacles and challenges without the use of drugs. Using Marx’s scheme, treatment providers should consider some of the environmental factors (i.e., poverty, financial issues) that may influence the youth’s drug abusive behavior and then address these issues during the process of treatment and rehabilitation in an effort to help the young Black male choose altemative ways of making a living and surviving in his environment. Treat-
ment programs that were Afrocentric in nature would take the
individual’s culture into consideration, thereby enabling service providers to address issues that are paramount to the African American population (such as high rate of unemployment, school dropout, financial issues, and the impact of racism on the youth’s psyche), many of which might otherwise be overlooked. Afrocentric programs would also focus on restructuring the youth’s value system and life purpose by providing him with material that stressed his rich African history and raised his thinking to a level higher than
that of materialism and individualism.
To be sure, there are no easy answers to the nation’s drug abuse problems. Ultimately, it is up to the individual to decide not to take drugs, but the author feels that the Black male’s environment (i.e., socioeconomic situation) can play a major role in his choice to use or sell drugs. All too often the victim is blamed for his condition without any further investigation of the factors that influenced his decision to participate in the behavior.
